    {
      "id": "line-000",
      "start": 0.0,
      "end": 5.86,
      "text": "This is a LibraVox recording. All LibraVox recordings are in the public domain.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-001",
      "start": 6.82,
      "end": 16.84,
      "text": "For more information and to find out how to volunteer, please visit LibraVox.org, recording by Marion Brown, Toronto, Canada.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-002",
      "start": 18.0,
      "end": 21.18,
      "text": "ASOP's Fables, the Eagle and his Captor.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-003",
      "start": 24.16,
      "end": 34.4,
      "text": "A man once caught an eagle, and after clipping his wings, turned him loose among the fowls in his henhouse, where he moped in a corner, looking very dejected and furlorn.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-004",
      "start": 35.08,
      "end": 41.24,
      "text": "After a while, his Captor was glad enough to sell him to a neighbor, who took him home and let his wings grow again.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-005",
      "start": 42.16,
      "end": 49.54,
      "text": "As soon as he had recovered the use of them, the Eagle flew out and caught a hair, which he brought home and presented to his benefactor.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-006",
      "start": 49.54,
      "end": 57.34,
      "text": "A fox observed this and said to the Eagle, don't waste your gifts on him. Go and give them to the man who first caught you.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-007",
      "start": 57.84,
      "end": 62.2,
      "text": "Make him your friend, then perhaps he won't catch you and clip your wings a second time.",
      "note": ""
    },
    {
      "id": "line-008",
      "start": 63.44,
      "end": 67.08,
      "text": "The end of the Eagle and his Captor.",
      "note": ""
    }
  ],
